{{Infobox rockunit | name = Ash Hollow Formation | image = | caption = | type = [[Formation (stratigraphy)|Formation]] | age = [[Neogene]] | prilithology = | otherlithology = | namedfor = | namedby = | region = [[South Dakota]] | country = [[United States]] | coordinates = | unitof = | subunits = | underlies = | overlies = | thickness = | extent = | area = | map = | map_caption = }}
The '''Ash Hollow Formation''' of the [[Ogallala Group]] is a [[geological formation]] found in [[Nebraska]] and [[South Dakota]]. It preserves [[fossils]] dating back to the [[Neogene]] [[Period (geology)|period]]. It was named after [[Ash Hollow, Nebraska]] and can be seen in [[Ash Hollow State Historical Park]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/267197598_Geologic_History_of_Ash_Hollow_State_Historical_Park_Nebraska | year = 1996 | title = Geologic History of Ash Hollow State Historical Park, Nebraska | publisher = University of Nebraska - Lincoln | author = Robert Diffendal, Jr., Roger K. Pabian, and J. R. Thomasson}}</ref>
==See also== {{Portal|Earth sciences|South Dakota|Paleontology|Neogene|Cenozoic}} * [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in South Dakota]] * [[Paleontology in South Dakota]]
