[[Image:Shale Greystanes NSW.JPG|thumb|Shale at [[Greystanes, New South Wales|Greystanes]], [[Australia]]]]
'''Bringelly Shale''' is a component of the [[Wianamatta shale|Wianammatta group]] of [[sedimentary]] rocks in the [[Sydney Basin]] of eastern [[Australia]]. It was formed in the [[Triassic]] [[Period (geology)|Period]]. It is most often seen in the western parts of the city. The shale has its greatest geographical extent at [[Bringelly]], near the suburb of [[Liverpool, New South Wales|Liverpool]]. It is similar to [[Ashfield Shale]], though differing in having a greater amount of [[sandstone]] and lacking [[siderite|sideritic]] [[mudstone]] bands. The average thickness is around 60 metres.<ref name=Museum>{{cite web|last=Lovering, J. F.|title=Bringelly Shale|url=http://australianmuseum.net.au/Uploads/Journals/17385/631_complete.pdf|work=STRATIGRAPHY OF' THE WIANAMATTA GROUP|publisher=Australian Museum|accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref> The Bringelly Shale was deposited in a swampy alluvial plain with meandering streams flowing from the west forming discontinuous beds of sandstone.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Chris Herbert |author2=Robin Helby |lastauthoramp=yes |title=A Guide to the Sydney basin|year=1980 |edition= 1st |publisher=Geological Survey of NSW|pages=582 |location=Maitland, NSW |isbn=978-0-7240-1250-3}}</ref>
==See also== [[Sydney Basin]], [[Hawkesbury sandstone]], [[Ashfield Shale]], [[Wianamatta shale]], [[Mittagong formation]] and [[Narrabeen Group]].
