In computing, '''Gist''' is a scientific graphics library written in [[C (programming language)|C]] by [[David H. Munro]] of [[Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory]]. It supports  three graphics output devices: [[X Window]], [[PostScript]], and [[Computer Graphics Metafile]]s (CGM). The library is promoted as being small (writing directly to Xlib), efficient, and full-featured. Portability is restricted to systems running [[X Window]] (essentially the [[Unix]] world).

There is a [[Python (programming language)|Python]] port called PyGist; it is used as one of several optional graphics front-ends of the scientific library [[SciPy]]. PyGist is also ported to [[Mac OS|Mac]] and [[MS Windows]].
