{{italic title}}
[[Image:The Mysteryes of Nature and Art bookcover.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Second edition cover]]
'''''The Mysteries of Nature and Art''''' is a book by John Bate written in 1634. The book acts as a practical guide for amateur scientific experiments, and is divided into four sections: '''Water Workes''', '''Fyer Workes''', '''Drawing, Colouring, Painting and Engraving''', and '''Divers Experiments'''.<ref name="brooke-hitching">Edward Brooke-Hitching. ''Fox Tossing, Octopus Wrestling, and Other Forgotten Sports'', p.102. Simon and Schuster, 2015. {{ISBN|978-1-4711-4899-6}}</ref> It inspired [[Isaac Newton]] during his younger years, in particular the section on '''fire Drakes''', kites with firecrackers tied to their tails.<ref name="brooke-hitching">Edward Brooke-Hitching. ''Fox Tossing, Octopus Wrestling, and Other Forgotten Sports'', p.102. Simon and Schuster, 2015. {{ISBN|978-1-4711-4899-6}}</ref> It contains one of the earliest depictions of fireworks and their preparation to be detailed in the English language, in a similar manner to the preceding ''[[De la pirotechnia]]''.

